reviews.title: A gem on the dike!
reviews.text: Dique, a gem on the dike! Lunched here this afternoon with 12 people. Everything checked out. A delicious three-course menu (fish), good wine (also alcohol-free), fine attentive service.

reviews.title: Delicious gluten-free lunch.
reviews.text: Indicated in advance that I have gluten intolerance was not a problem.  The waitress explained everything I could and could not eat gluten-free from the menu. Also after delicious mini gluten-free pastry on.  Really great food and very nice service.

reviews.title: Empty terrace but no place.
reviews.text: We went for a bike ride, we wanted to have a coffee. Outside was more than enough space, but three tables occupied out of twelve. Within ten minutes everything would be taken we were told. We were turned away. Fifteen minutes at the bikes confer. All the tables just stayed empty. So, in 15 minutes, I don't see anyone coming. That's not how you treat your customers. Pragmatic solution was not offered to us. Tables remained unoccupied. We just didn't want to have a cup of coffee anymore.

reviews.title: Beautiful and delicious dishes.
reviews.text:
Dinner for the first time, after having lunch here earlier.
Beautiful dishes and delicious taste.
Fine and correct service.
Will definitely be back here.

reviews.title: Absolutely recommended
reviews.text:
What a nice location 
Pleasant service and attractively priced 
The “open wines” are okay in terms of price, but quality should be even better with a few Euros more per bottle

reviews.title: Good restaurant
reviews.text:
We had a great meal there 
Good service very friendly.
Nice location and plenty of parking. 
Definitely worth repeating.

reviews.title: Top, good value for money and very friendly staff
reviews.text: Eating here for the second time, last month for dinner, now for lunch with a customer. It was like last time again: friendly staff, good quality at a reasonable price. Good food and a satisfied customer. My afternoon can't go wrong.

reviews.title: Nice restaurant, great food, top service.
reviews.text: What a nice place to eat. Delicious dishes not too big. Really very nice service you are super well taken care of. Many products from our own garden and locally. Delicious wine. In short, Knight Church has a beautiful restaurant.

reviews.title: Surprising, very good value for money and very friendly service.
reviews.text: First time eaten here, were with friends who are used to a high level. So always exciting. But that tension was for nothing. We had a wonderful meal here. Just a little different, distinctive.  A very good value for money. Not to mention the very good service. Attention and kindness present in a casual manner. Everything was great!

reviews.title: A gem on the dike
reviews.text: What a surprise, delicious food in a very nice atmosphere and with super nice service. We will definitely come back here. The deer on the menu is certainly not inferior to the game restaurants in the Achterhoek. The white wine from Thorn is also recommended. In short, a great experience

reviews.title: Recommended!
reviews.text: We ate here for the 3rd time. The quality is consistent and very high. Good flavor combinations with matching wines. Ambience is very relaxed, the service is very attentive.

reviews.title: Nicely located and good atmosphere
reviews.text: This restaurant is beautifully located on the dike with plenty of parking and a good base for a walk. Good service and reception with tasty food. The wines are a bit on the expensive side. All in all, definitely worth a try.

reviews.title: Atmospheric, beautiful menu with carefully chosen wine arrangement
reviews.text:
Dique hasn't been open for long. Dinner only on Friday and Saturday evenings.
Beautiful 4-course menu with subtle dishes, star ratings without the associated absurd price.
Value for your money
Nice wines: excellent arrangement.
Great cook and very hospitable owner couple.
I go here more often

articleContent.title: Your go-to guide for dog-friendly travel

seoInfo.metaDescription: Traveling with your dog has never been easier—or more fun. Cities across the country boast pet-friendly hotels, parks, and activities. With CESAR® brand’s mission to make the world more pet-friendly and Tripadvisor’s top-rated spots, you can plan with confidence. Whether it’s a quick getaway or a bucket-list trip, our guides help you stay, play, and explore with your pup. Grab the leash and go!

articleContent.title: Where centuries-old traditions continue to inspire

seoInfo.metaDescription: A visit to Japan is incomplete without experiencing the Kansai region. Regarded as the country’s cultural heart, it’s home to cities like the ever-popular Kyoto and the towering culinary hub of Osaka—this year’s World Expo host.

I’ve always loved train travel. There’s something special about settling into a window seat and watching the landscape drift past. And as a wheelchair user, that joy only grows when the journey feels easy: level boarding, space to move, and the kind of accessibility that lets you fully relax. For me, the best train rides—like weaving through the Tuscan countryside on Trenitalia—are never just a way to get from A to B; they're part of the adventure.

tripContent.title: Celebrate Nevada's history, rhythm, and culture
tripContent.description: Nevada’s story is etched in historic mining towns, roadside wonders, galleries, and museums. From frontier heritage and atomic relics to glowing neon art, every stop reveals a new layer of the state's past and present. Whether you're wandering small-town streets or stepping into iconic city museums, this journey blends memory and motion in a way that’s anything but ordinary.

tripContent.title: Santa Fe: heritage & history on the Original Route 66
tripContent.description: Looking for adventure on the original Route 66? Santa Fe, the oldest state capital, is a must-stop for history buffs. The city, founded in 1610, is older than the United States—but the area has been populated for well over a thousand years. With so much history and heritage, you'll want to allow plenty of time to explore the best of the Southwest—so here are 12 suggestions for things to see, do, and learn.
